Problem 2. Graphical models (40 pts)

2.1

Estimate a partial correlation graph with the bootstrap using 500 bootstrap draws (typically, we would use more, but this is a HW afterall). Draw an edge between two nodes if 0 is not in the bootstrap interval. Remember: Omega_jk = 0 means the two features are partially uncorrelated given every other feature.

B = 500 #### Answer 2.1.1
        
Rhat_starOutput = array(dim=c(p,p,B))
for(b in 1:B){
    bootSamp      = sample(1:n,n,replace=TRUE)
    Xpc_star      = X[bootSamp,]
    Spc_star      = cov(Xpc_star)
    OmegaHat_star = solve(Spc_star)
    Rhat_star     = -diag(1/sqrt(diag(OmegaHat_star))) %*% OmegaHat_star  %*% diag(1/sqrt(diag(OmegaHat_star)))
    Rhat_starOutput[,,b] = Rhat_star    
}


#### Answer 2.1.2: Print the lower 0.005 quantile of the bootstrap draws for the first 5 features only
Q_lower = apply(Rhat_starOutput,1:2, quantile, 0.005)
Q_lower[1:5,1:5]

#### Answer 2.1.4: produce a partial correlation graph using these bootstrap confidence intervals
noEdge = 0 > apply(Rhat_starOutput,1:2, quantile, 0.005) & 0 < apply(Rhat_starOutput,1:2, quantile, 0.995)

g = graph.adjacency(!noEdge , mode="undirected", diag=FALSE )
plot(g, layout=layout.auto,
     vertex.color='white',vertex.size=3,vertex.label=names(X),vertex.frame.color=NA)

2.2

Lets investigate if the partial correlation graph interpretation can be strengthened to conditional independence in this case.

#### Answer 2.2.1: Plot the QQplots looking at some of the marginal distributions 
par(mfrow= c(3,3))
for(j in 1:p){
  qqnorm(X[,j])
  qqline(X[,j],col = 'red')
}

#### Answer 2.2.2: Get the QQplot  with respect to the beta distribution
alp = (p-2)/(2*p)
bet = (n-p-3)/(2*(n-p-1))
a   = p/2
b   = (n-p-1)/2

probs = (1:n - alp)/(n - alp - bet +1)
quantiles = qbeta(probs,a,b)


Xcenter = scale(X, center=TRUE,scale=FALSE)
S=1/(n-1)*t(Xcenter) %*% Xcenter
Dsq = rep(0,n)
for(i in 1:n){
  Dsq[i] = t(Xcenter[i,]) %*% solve(S) %*% Xcenter[i,]
}
u = n * Dsq/(n-1)**2
par(mfrow=c(1,1))
plot(quantiles,sort(u),type='l',xlab='beta quantile',ylab = 'u quantile')

Answer 2.2.3

Looking at this data, is it reasonable to extend these results to conditional independence?

It is not reasonable to extend these results to conditional independence. Those results could be consedered as conditional independence only if marginal distributions are normal distributions. However, according to these Q-Q plots, we did not see the points forming a line thats roughly straight. That means those data are not normal distribution, so it is not reasonable to extend these results to conditional independence.

Answer 2.2.4

Write down an interpretation of this graphical model (it shouldnt be comprehensive, just interpret some aspect of the graphical model. One or two short sentences is fine).

We used beta quantile, which is a normal distribution, to compare with our data. As the points did not form a line thats roughly straight, so we could check the normality byt this graphical model and knew that our data is not normal distributed.

2.3 (Extra Credit, this problem is optional and worth +10 pts)

Lets instead attempt to transform our data to something more normal. For this section, lets just look at the capitalization features. Write up a function for finding a the multivariate Box-cox transformation, transform the data, and then re-make the marginal qqplots.

X = Xfull %>% select(contains('cap'))
p = ncol(X)

S_lamF = function(lam, X){ #### Answer 2.3.1. Compute the sample covariance matrix on the transformed data  
    Xcenter = scale( t( (t(X) ** lam)/lam - 1 ) ,center=TRUE,scale=FALSE)
    return(1/(n-1)* t(Xcenter) %*% Xcenter)
}
logLikeF = function(lam, X){ #### Answer 2.3.2. Compute the sample covariance matrix on the transformed data    
    S_lam = S_lamF(lam, X)
    return(-n/2 * log(det(S_lam)) + sum( (lam - 1) * apply(log(X),2,sum)) ) 
}

lam = c(0.0001, 0.0005, 0.001,.0025,.005,.01,.05)#these values are due to the type of skew
lamGrid = expand.grid(lam,lam,lam)
out = apply(lamGrid,1,logLikeF, X)

lambdaHat = unlist(lamGrid[which.max(out),])

Xtrans = t( (t(X) ** lambdaHat)/lambdaHat - 1 )

par(mfrow= c(1,3))
for(j in 1:p){
  qqnorm(Xtrans[,j])
  qqline(Xtrans[,j],col = 'red')
}

I found the transformation parameter lambda to be 10^{-4}, 0.0025, 10^{-4}.

Answer 3.3.3

Why do you think there isnt much difference between the scaled and unscaled PCA for this data set?

As a general rule, we use scale if the features are measured in different units. If features are in the different units, our results may be distorted, and thats why we need to scale them. However, in this case, those stock prices are in the same units, so there isnt much difference between the scaled and unscaled PCA for this data set.
